§§ Belonging ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ As a second example, consider the symbol $∈$. ⦉

  ‖ Let $a$ denote an object and let $A$ denote a set. ⦉

  <!--
  <div data-littype='run'> ❲%Let us suppose that the object denoted by $a$ belongs to the set denoted by $A$ (see \sheetref{sets}{Sets}).❳ </div>
  -->

  ‖ We agree that $∈$ means “belongs to” in the sense of “is
    an element of” or “is a member of” (see␣
    <a href='/sheets/sets.html'>
      ‖ Sets ⦉
    </a>
    ). ⦉

  ‖ Then we write $a ∈ A$. ⦉

  ‖ We read these symbols as “the object denoted by $a$ belongs
    to the set denoted by $A$”.
    † ⦊
      ‖ The symbol $∈$ is a stylized lower case Greek letter
        $ϵ$, which is a mnemonic for the ancient Greek word 
$\grave{\epsilon} \sigma \tau \acute{\iota}$
        <!--ἐστί-->
        which means, roughly, “belongs”. ⦉

      ‖ Since in English, $ϵ$ is read aloud “ehp-sih-lawn,” $∈$
        is also a mnemonic for “element of”. ⦉
    ⦉⦉
⦉

¶ ⦊
  ‖ The symbol $∈$ is not symmetric. ⦉

  ‖ If we flip it left and right it looks different. ⦉

  ‖ This reflects that $a ∈ A$ does not the mean the same as
    $A ∈ a$ (see␣
    <a href='/sheets/sets.html'>
      ‖ Sets ⦉
    </a>
    ). ⦉

  ‖ As with english words, the order of symbols is significant. ⦉

  ‖ The word “word” is not the same as the word “drow”. ⦉

  <!--
  <div data-littype='run'> ❲%The symmetry of identity $=$ is special.❳ </div>
  -->

  ‖ Our symbolism for belonging reflects the concept’s lack of
    symmetry. ⦉
⦉

